Title: Independence Day: Resurgence | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: I'll admit that they could've done way better on this movie. When it comes to sequels, they're not always that great; nothing beats an original. However, the idea of the Alien Queen was interesting. There are two main things I would've changed to the movie: No CGI aliens (Make them look realistic like back in 1996) and make the plot a little more serious. Me and some of my friends thought it was filmed for a more younger audience unlike the first movie. And the story seemed too rushed for some reason. The introduction of another extraterrestrial race is interesting, a more peaceful one than invasive, but could've gotten into way more detail about them. One thing I really liked is how they brought Dylan back from the first movie now as a grown young man taking after his father. In other words, the movie was fairly okay to watch, but like most sequels attempting to be as good as the original, they could've put a little more effort into developing it a tad better. After I came out of the theater I said to my friends "the trailer was better than the movie itself".

Comment:
Perhaps if you are tired or drunk the movie would get a solid 7/10. Otherwise, I would give it a 5/10 or perhaps a 6/10.. and that is out of generosity.

Also, what is up with the larger alien ships and bigger weapons? Was that supposed to be more scary and dangerous to give the movie more excitement? Well, I do not think it really did the movie justice to be fair. It is really missing the charm like in the first movie, and they did not need to have such big weapons and alien ships to make that movie as good as it is. And what is up with all the patriotism and American flags all over the place? Especially with the exclamations that "We are going to save the world becuase we are Americans"? I thought the whole world of nations came together to fight against the alien invasion, not just America.

**Warning, Spoiler alert**: The Queen could not strictly shoot/hit a school bus driving in a (fairly) straight line, but can without a problem knock out and shoot out a bunch of flying attack planes.. Cmon, really?

Nah, it is not a great movie or anything along those lines... but it is a time-killer, that is for certain.

Final score: 15/30

Comment:
A 150 million dollar introduction to a new series that will try to fill the hole stargate left.... possibly... lets hope so.... 

The movie went alright until the aliens show up with the "even bigger" ship this time. That ship was so big if it landed on earth for real it would've destroyed the planet, even passing earth would've made huge damage. and yet there it was parking accross the atlantic ocean somehow affecting china's cities. 

The end was the worst, I think the script writers realised in what huge sh-t the huumans were in and with no plausible escape they invented the hive queen thing... why did the alien fighters fell from the sky when the queen died is beyond me but if it wasn't done even without a queen the aliens would've won.... They almost did it right with the human forces fighting the aliens inside the huge ship in that alien environment but that scene was terribly short and terribly misused.

The sfx or cgi was awesome, pure eye candy as most of modern films,  So if you like that sort of stuff you'l be pleased.

The disappointment comes from the script point of view.

Comment:
For a lot of people the 20-years-after-secuels are kind of pointless, but I personally think this movie has a lot of sense in the making, why? Most of the authors of aliens books say that if someday we are visited by an extraterrestrial race, there are two chances; 1.- They come to help us in our development as race and society teaching us the use of technology for a better life quality; 2.- They're hostiles, here are two more possibilities, a) They won and take over the planet, b) They lose but they come back with renforcements and try again, so considering all of this, is more than logic that they would come back as per the 20 years after maybe for them there wasn't 20 years, remember all the Interstellar stuff about time in space, they're probably getting back right after they knew they were defeated:

Other points that worth to be mentioned:

- President Whitmore dreaming about 'they're coming back'. Has a lot of sense, why? Remember one of them get into his brain, and intencionally (or not) they created a connection with a human, so it's logic Mr. President can see or feel things, specially because aliens use Telekinesis to communicate each other.

- Using their technology, David Levinson says that is to strengthen our planet, maybe that wasn't the first intention but it makes sense, how often can you make experiments out of a completely new technology.

- Different space ships and plan, of course if their original plan didn't work they must use another tactics and better gear.

In an essence this movie is going to be a rehash of the first film, except this time the humans have the alien technology combined with their own, to defeat the second wave of aliens.

Feels kind of like a mix of Independence Day, Gravity and Star Wars rolled into one, whether or not that will be a good thing and works is yet to be seen. 

It will be interesting to see how this movie pans out. The only thing is in the first film, it kind of contradicts the second. When the president learns from the alien, they carry  their whole civilization going from worlds to worlds. 

So I'm wondering a new wave could have come if they were all destroyed in the first, unless a second ship remained behind the moon and evacuated on the destruction of the first mothership.

If you watched the debut trailer for Independence Day: Resurgence that dropped earlier today, you probably noticed an interesting lack of Will Smith's Steven Hiller. Title: Independence Day: Resurgence | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
For whatever reason (his reasons probably), Will Smith is not in this and that is going to hurt this movie. When Independence Day came out in 1996, the super, overblown scifi blockbuster was NOT the norm, so the (spectacular) special effects could sell the movie alone. Having a fun, solid cast was just the icing on the cake. Now that every other flick coming out has giant aliens/spaceships/robots/explosions/graphic cg warfare in it, the only thing that will make a film like this stand out is a fun, solid cast.Will Smith plus Jeff Goldblum has my ticket sold. Just Jeff Goldblum (whom I love, don't get me wrong)... has me waiting to read the tomatometer.  

Regarding special effects and theatrical action... what was new and exciting in '96 is repetitive and mundane today. But good characters and story never get old. This trailer didn't sell me on the characters and story.

I was also disappointed to see no Will Smith, but really, if you think about it, he's not that good of an actor in certain kinds of movies, and this is one of them. He doesn't pull off serious very well all the time (sometimes, but not all the time). His goofy smile is nearly impossible to hide when it's time to be deadly serious, so it betrays the required emotions on the screen. This movie might end up being better without him.

It's either (1) his schedule couldn't accommodate ID:R, (2) Fox didn't want to pony up $20+ million, or (3) the screenplay is so bad that Will said no to $20+ million. Let's hope it ain't numero 3.

Title: Independence Day: Resurgence | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
The way I always picture a sequel in my head, although it's a little clich√©, is that when alien connected telepathically with the President it was too much information all at once and he only saw glimpses of the last part of the connection. Over time, it slowly started unravelling and the consciousness of the alien was imprinted in his mind, driving him partly mad with the information, and weakening his constitution to the point where he was mentally being taken over by the alien consciousness.
Secretly, it was keeping the President under control subconsciously. It waited until it had enough control to make him fulfill tasks, and made him send a message out to the main alien fleet once humans had reversed engineered the tech to use their power source, and their communication technology. During/After, he was discovered. The President, in a moment of lucidity, agreed he needed to be kept locked away or in solitary, but no one could tell if the alien was still in control or not and just agreeing to save itself, if the he was still under control, or if the alien was also slowly being influenced by the human memories/emotions/etc and falling back to more even ground mentally with the President/human, since he was openly telling them about the information that was unravelling in his mind as he was going mad. 

Another aspect being that their entire civilization only became "like locusts" because they were driven off by another race that behaved the same way. With their civilization's home destroyed, they obsessed over it. The militarization of their entire race started happening, vowing that it would never be a victim again, but the victors. They started engineering themselves biologically for war and occupation, intially not destroying worlds but forcefully occupying them. Over time, they cared less and less about saving life from extinction as they occupied and saw it as a hindrance on their goals. The military-like leaders put in a type of emotional block while growing new soldiers so they would not disobey orders and do what needed to be done. They started going from one system to another just like those who drove them from their own world.
The alien's partial consciousness in the ex-President's mind, being exposed to the human emotions confused and started affectimg it, breaking down some of the emotional blocking it had, making it go a bit insane as well trying to understand and process it. With them both kinda losing it, they started understanding one better, having lucid mental conversations of a sort for short periods of time.

I had many more ideas of how to go about it, but I'll leave it at that. Thanks for reading, anyone who took the time. :) Peace.
